Hotel bookings - factors

library(tidyverse)
library(skimr)
library(scales)
library(forcats)
# From TidyTuesday: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2020/2020-02-11/readme.md
hotels <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-02-11/hotels.csv")

First, knit the document and view the following visualization.

hotels %>%
  group_by(hotel, arrival_date_month) %>%   # group by hotel type and arrival month
  summarise(mean_adr = mean(adr)) %>%       # calculate mean adr for each group
  ggplot(aes(
    x = arrival_date_month,                 # x-axis = arrival_date_month
    y = mean_adr,                           # y-axis = mean_adr calculated above
    group = hotel,                          # group lines by hotel type
    color = hotel)                          # and color by hotel type
    ) +
  geom_line() +                             # use lines to represent data
  theme_minimal() +                         # use a minimal theme
  labs(x = "Arrival month",                 # customize labels
       y = "Mean ADR (average daily rate)",
       title = "Comparison of resort and city hotel prices across months",
       subtitle = "Resort hotel prices soar in the summer while ciry hotel prices remain relatively constant throughout the year",
       color = "Hotel type")

Brexit Data Viz

In September 2019, YouGov survey asked 1,639 GB adults the following question:

In hindsight, do you think Britain was right/wrong to vote to leave EU?

  • Right to leave
  • Wrong to leave
  • Donât know The data from the survey is in data/brexit.csv.
brexit <- read_csv("data/brexit.csv")

In the course video we made the following visualization.

brexit <- brexit %>%
  mutate(
    region = fct_relevel(region, "london", "rest_of_south", "midlands_wales", "north", "scot"),
    region = fct_recode(region, London = "london", `Rest of South` = "rest_of_south", `Midlands / Wales` = "midlands_wales", North = "north", Scotland = "scot")
  )
ggplot(brexit, aes(y = opinion, fill = opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region, nrow = 1, labeller = label_wrap_gen(width = 12)) +
  guides(fill = FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Was Britain right/wrong to vote to leave EU?",
    subtitle = "YouGov Survey Results, 2-3 September 2019",
    caption = "Source: bit.ly/2lCJZVg",
    x = NULL, y = NULL
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Wrong" = "#ef8a62",
    "Right" = "#67a9cf",
    "Don't know" = "gray"
  )) +
  theme_minimal()

In this application exercise we tell different stories with the same data.

Exercise 1 - Free scales

Add scales = "free_x" as an argument to the facet_wrap() function. How does the visualization change? How is the story this visualization telling different than the story the original plot tells?

ggplot(brexit, aes(y = opinion, fill = opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  facet_wrap(~region,
    nrow = 1, labeller = label_wrap_gen(width = 12),

Exercise 2 - Comparing proportions across facets

First, calculate the proportion of wrong, right, and donât know answers in each category and then plot these proportions (rather than the counts) and then improve axis labeling. How is the story this visualization telling different than the story the original plot tells? Hint: Youâll need the scales package to improve axis labeling.

ggplot(brexit, aes(y = opinion, fill = opinion)) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = (..count../sum(..count..))), position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~region,
    nrow = 1, labeller = label_wrap_gen(width = 12)
  ) +
  guides(fill = "none") +
  labs(
    title = "Was Britain right/wrong to vote to leave EU?",
    subtitle = "YouGov Survey Results, 2-3 September 2019",
    caption = "Source: bit.ly/2lCJZVg",
    x = NULL, y = NULL
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(
    "Wrong" = "#ef8a62",
    "Right" = "#67a9cf",
    "Don't know" = "gray"
  )) +
  theme_minimal()

Exercise 3 -

Next we will run a t-test comparing two means. In order to do this, I will first select a categorical variable of interest, convert it to a factor/save it in a new variable, and view the levels.

anime$rating_FACTOR <- as.factor(anime$rating)
levels(anime$rating_FACTOR)
## [1] "G - All Ages"                   "None"                          
## [3] "PG - Children"                  "PG-13 - Teens 13 or older"     
## [5] "R - 17+ (violence & profanity)" "R+ - Mild Nudity"

As you see, we have 6 different levels. In order to run a t-test we must select only two. I am going to select âG - All Agesâ and âR - 17+ (violence & profanity)â. First I create a new dataset called anime_ttest, next I filter for the two levela of interest, and finally I drop the levels not being used.

anime_ttest <- anime %>%
  filter(rating_FACTOR == "G - All Ages" | 
           rating_FACTOR == "R - 17+ (violence & profanity)") 

anime_ttest$rating_FACTOR <- droplevels(anime_ttest$rating_FACTOR)

Now I can run my t-test. I am going to test if there is a significant difference in popularity based on rating. Interpret the t-test results.

t.test(popularity ~ rating_FACTOR, data = anime_ttest)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  popularity by rating_FACTOR
## t = 63.723, df = 1390, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  7298.198 7761.808
## sample estimates:
##                   mean in group G - All Ages 
##                                    11296.599 
## mean in group R - 17+ (violence & profanity) 
##                                     3766.596

Exercise 4 -

Below I have created a basic ggplot to observe the differences. Your task is to improve the graph by: Cleaning up all of the labels, adding a title, make each bar a different color, and add a theme. See https://ggplot2-book.org/polishing.html for a list of included themes. Finally, interpret what you see.

ggplot(anime_ttest, aes(rating_FACTOR, popularity, fill = rating_FACTOR)) +

  guides(fill = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "mako") +

Exercise 5 -

I want to see how anime popularity is influenced by rating type. However, I do not want to be limited to 2 levels. Therefore, I am going to run a linear regression. In the video for this week I showed one way to run a linear regression. Today I am going to show you another way. Itâs all about personal preference at the end of the day.

library(moderndive)
anime.mod.1 <- lm(popularity ~ as.factor(rating), data = anime )

When interpreting the output of a linear regression with one categorical predictor, we interpret the output in a specific way. R is going to select a âbaselineâ level and all other levels will be compared to it. How do we know which level will be the baseline? It is whichever level appears first and is usually alphabetical. Below we see that G - All Ages is the first level and therefore is our baseline.

levels(as.factor(anime$rating))
## [1] "G - All Ages"                   "None"                          
## [3] "PG - Children"                  "PG-13 - Teens 13 or older"     
## [5] "R - 17+ (violence & profanity)" "R+ - Mild Nudity"

Now I want to look at my regression output. I am going to do this with the get_regression_table() function.

get_regression_table(anime.mod.1, print = TRUE)
term estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
intercept 11296.599 50.230 224.899 0.000 11198.142 11395.056
as.factor(rating)None -166.288 182.255 -0.912 0.362 -523.532 190.956
as.factor(rating)PG - Children -2098.933 110.135 -19.058 0.000 -2314.812 -1883.054
as.factor(rating)PG-13 - Teens 13 or older -6092.506 70.319 -86.641 0.000 -6230.342 -5954.671
as.factor(rating)R - 17+ (violence & profanity) -7530.003 121.782 -61.832 0.000 -7768.713 -7291.293
as.factor(rating)R+ - Mild Nudity -6134.238 130.363 -47.055 0.000 -6389.767 -5878.709

Here is how we interpret the output:

  • The intercept is our baseline. This is the popularity of G - All Ages
  • The None row contains the estimate of -166.288, but the p value is 0.362 and therefore not significant/interpretable.
  • The PG - Children row contains the estimate of -2098.933 and a p < 0.05. This estimate is the adjustment to the intercept we make when wanting to get the estimate of popularity of PG - Children. The estimate is negative which means PG - Children is less popular than G - All Ages. The popularity of PG - Children is 9197.666.
  • The PG-13 - Teens 13 or older row contains the estimate of -6092.506 and a p < 0.05. This estimate is the adjustment to the intercept we make when wanting to get the estimate of popularity of PG-13 - Teens 13 or older. The estimate is negative which means PG-13 - Teens 13 or older is less popular than G - All Ages. The popularity of PG-13 - Teens 13 or older is 5204.093.
  • The R - 17+ (violence & profanity) row contains the estimate of -7530.003 and a p < 0.05. This estimate is the adjustment to the intercept we make when wanting to get the estimate of popularity of R - 17+ (violence & profanity). The estimate is negative which means R - 17+ (violence & profanity) is less popular than G - All Ages. The popularity of R - 17+ (violence & profanity) is 3766.596.
  • The R+ - Mild Nudity row contains the estimate of -6134.238 and a p < 0.05. This estimate is the adjustment to the intercept we make when wanting to get the estimate of popularity of R+ - Mild Nudity. The estimate is negative which means R+ - Mild Nudity is less popular than G - All Ages. The popularity of R+ - Mild Nudity is 5162.361.
